Trajectory reconstruction using wavelet filtering
The MPEG-4 movie, jzsmall.mp4, shows a counter-rotation of the methyl and methylene groups characterizing the quasiperiodic segments of the trajectory. The progress of the trajectory on the spectrogram of Figure 2 is shown on the right-hand panel of the movie. On the left-hand side are two representations of the same ethyl radical. The lower representation shows the complete motion as the radical traverses the trajectory. The upper representation shows the filtered motion, filtered meaning that the density plots on the 21 spectrograms corresponding to the 21 Cartesian degrees of freedom are truncated to eliminate non-periodic contributions to the motion, and then inverse transformed to visualize the quasiperiodic parts of the trajectory. At the very beginning and the very end of the trajectory, there are artifactual differences due to edge effects. These appear when the trajectory is outside of the cone of influence marked by the dotted line on the spectrogram.

Selecting a training set and HCTH147 parameter fitting
Ethyl radical energized with 120 kcal/mol total energy will sample nuclear configurations during the trajectories that are far away from the ethyl equilibrium geometry. Following the work of Collins [Theor. Chem. Acc. 108, 313 (2002)], we ran 449 classical trajectories at the UHF/631G* level (results in the next section) and sequentially selected 67 nuclear configurations of ethyl radical most frequently visited by the classical trajectories but far from existing data points in the data set using the h(k) method. We then added those 67 geometries (see Table III) with single point energies calculated at the CCSD(T)/cc-pVTZ level to the training and validation data set. We then used this data set to obtain specific reaction parameters (SRP) for the HCTH147 exchange-correlation density functional representing the global PES of ethyl radical. A least-square fit (L-BFGS-B) minimized the weighted relative energy and gradient differences between the coupled-clusters reference data set and HCTH-SRP. Gradient data was only included for the stationary points. The fitted parameters significantly improved the accuracy of the functional over the starting parameters from HTCH147 parameterized with the TZ2P basis set [A. D. Boese, N. L. Doltsinis, N. C. Handy, and M. Sprik, J. Chem. Phys. 112, 1670 (2000)]. Boese et al. [J. Chem. Phys. 119, 3005 (2003)] recently parameterized the HCTH147 functional using different basis sets, including 6-31+G** (HCTH147@6-31+G**). Our HCTH-SRP/631G** outperforms HCTH147@6-31+G**/6-31G** for relative energies and reaction energies,

It is important to note that well below 5 eV (~ 120 kcal/mol), the probability distribution has gone to zero. In Ref. (41) of the main text, Troe and Ushakov indicated that classical trajectories can enter an unphysical regime in which the internal energy falls below the zero-point energy of the molecule. Such trajectories must be discarded. Troe and Ushakov showed numerical examples of initial canonical energy distributions in which the effect was large at low temperatures, but became negligible at high temperatures. As a spot-check to see if there is any significant cause for concern in the present work, the trajectories are checked at the dissociation limit where the kinetic energy release must be greater than 120 kcal/mol for a trajectory to become unphysical. The KERD goes asymptotically to zero by 50 kcal/mol which simply indicates that the initial microcanonical energy distribution with 120 kcal/mol above the zeropoint energy is analogous to Troe and Ushakov's high temperature case.
